# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] The **110th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government, between January 3, 2007, and January 3, 2009, during the last two years of the Presidency of George W.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] It was composed of the Senate and the House of Representatives.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] The apportionment of seats in the House was based on the 2000 U.S. census.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] The Democratic Party won a majority in both chambers, giving them full control of Congress for the first time since the 103rd Congress in 1993, which was also the previous time they controlled the House.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] Officially in the Senate, there were 49 Democrats, 49 Republicans, and two independents, but because both of the independents caucused with the Democrats, this gave the Democrats an operational majority.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] No Democratic-held seats had fallen to the Republican Party in the 2006 elections.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] This is the most recent Congress to feature Republican senators from Minnesota (Norm Coleman), New Mexico (Pete Domenici) and Oregon (Gordon Smith), in which Domenici retired and the other two lost re-election at the end of the Congress.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] Democrat Nancy Pelosi became the first female speaker of the House.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] The House also received the first Muslim (Keith Ellison) and Buddhist (Hank Johnson and Mazie Hirono) members of Congress.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] Members debated initiatives such as the Democrats' 100-Hour Plan and the Iraq War troop surge of 2007.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] Following President Bush's 2007 State of the Union Address, Congress debated his proposal to create a troop surge to increase security in Iraq.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] The House of Representatives passed a non-binding measure opposing the surge and then a $124 billion emergency spending measure to fund the war, which included language that dictated troop levels and withdrawal schedules.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] President Bush, however, vetoed the bill as promised, making this his second veto while in office.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] Both houses of Congress subsequently passed a bill funding the war without timelines, but with benchmarks for the Iraqi government and money for other spending projects like disaster relief.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] These are partial lists of prominent enacted legislation and pending bills.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] Membership changed with one death and two resignations.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] Membership fluctuated with seven deaths and eight resignations.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p01] There were two resignations and one death.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p02] Lists of committees and their party leaders for members of the House and Senate committees can be found through the Official Congressional Directory at the bottom of this article.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p02] The directory after the pages of terms of service lists committees of the Senate, House (Standing with Subcommittees, Select and Special) and Joint and, after that, House/Senate committee assignments.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/110th-united-states-congress-p02] On the committees section of the House and Senate in the Official Congressional Directory, the committee's members on the first row on the left side shows the chairman of the committee and on the right side shows the ranking member of the committee.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] The **111th United States Congress** was a meeting of the legislative branch of the United States federal government from January 3, 2009, until January 3, 2011.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] It began during the last weeks of the George W.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] Bush administration, with the remainder spanning the first two years of Barack Obama's presidency.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] However, the Senate supermajority only lasted for a period of 72 working days while the Senate was actually in session.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] A new delegate seat was created for the Northern Mariana Islands.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] The 111th Congress had the most long-serving members in history: at the start of the 111th Congress, the average member of the House had served 10.3 years, while the average Senator had served 13.4 years.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] The Democratic Party would not simultaneously control both the U.S.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] Senate again until more than a decade later, during the 117th Congress.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] After comprising the majority of the House of Representatives since the 106th United States Congress, the 111th United States Congress was the first where Baby boomers comprised the majority of the Senate.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] The 111th Congress was the most productive congress since the 89th Congress.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] It enacted numerous significant pieces of legislation, including the Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act, the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act, the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act, the Dodd–Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, and the New START treaty.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] An election dispute over the Minnesota seat previously held by Norm Coleman (R), between Coleman and challenger Al Franken (D), was decided on June 30, 2009, in favor of Franken.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] Franken's admission briefly gave the Senate Democratic caucus 60 votes, enough to defeat a filibuster in a party-line vote.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] At the encouragement of the Obama administration, Congress devoted significant time considering health care reform.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] In March 2010, Obama signed the Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act into law, the first comprehensive health care reform legislation in decades, along with further amendments in the Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] In this Congress, Class 3 meant their term ended with this Congress, requiring reelection in 2010; Class 1 meant their term began in the last Congress, requiring reelection in 2012; and Class 2 meant their term began in this Congress, requiring reelection in 2014.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] Five changes are associated with appointments to the Obama Administration, four directly and one indirectly.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] Two representatives changed parties, one died, and five resigned.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] House vacancies are only filled by elections.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/111th-united-states-congress-p01] State laws regulate when (and if) there will be special elections.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The **1876 Colorado gubernatorial election** took place on October 3, 1876, to elect the 1st Governor of Colorado after the state was admitted to the union on August 1, 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Republican John Long Routt, last governor of the Colorado Territory, was elected in a close race against Democratic nominee Bela M.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] McCook, who already had been territorial Governor from 1869 to 1873, was appointed for another term by President Ulysses S.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Grant after incumbent Governor Samuel Elbert had been removed due to misconduct in the Land Office in Pueblo.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Elbert had supporters that claimed he should not have been relieved from his office because he was not involved in any misconduct.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] McCook, whose first administration was considered tainted by corruption, was also fiercely opposed by Jerome B.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Chaffee, an Elbert supporter, who was the Territory's Delegate to the House of Representative at the time.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Many in the territory saw McCook's appointment as an affront.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The battle for his Senate confirmation turned into a feud between Chaffee and President Grant.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Chaffee even threatened to resign if McCook was confirmed in the Senate.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] After five months of testimony and multiple accusations against McCook, the Senate confirmed his appointment on June 19, 1874, by a one-vote majority.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] After he had returned to Colorado, Governor McCook asked President Grant to relieve all political appointees from their duties, which had been recommended by Delegate Chaffee.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] President Grant complied and appointed replacements that all lived outside the territory.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] McCook and those other federal officers were considered carpetbaggers by the local population.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] There was a growing a sentiment in the territory, that the federal offices were used to place unsuccessful and no longer needed politicians from the east of the United States.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] A growing dissatisfaction with the Republican president, his local appointees and the infighting in the Republican party led to the surprising victory of Democrat Thomas M.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Patterson in the election for Delegate to the House of Representatives on November 3, 1874.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] McCook's second term as Governor was not successful and lasted just eight months.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] His administration was plagued by infighting in the Republican Party and McCook's personal problems.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] McCook was distraught by the death of his wife Mary and suffered from alcoholism.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] His lack of moral conduct cost him a lot of support and in February 1875 he resigned at the request of President Grant.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] On March 29, 1875, Republican John Long Routt was appointed by President Grant as to replace the unpopular Edward McCook as Governor of the Territory of Colorado.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] President Grant and John Routt had been close friends since their serving together for the Union in the Civil War.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Routt's first task was to unite the local Republican party after years of infighting.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] He also needed to solve a growing disconnect between the inhabitants of Denver and the inhabitants of more rural areas in the territory.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Many rural Coloradions believed that the gridlock and infighting in the years prior had been caused by a strong concentration of power for Denver politicians.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] At first, Routt had to deal with skepticism because he had also been appointed to the office without ever living in Colorado before.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] He reassured the public by stating that he planned to move to the territory even if he had not been appointed as Governor.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] His term as territorial Governor was dominated by the crafting of the first State Constitution of Colorado by the 1875 constitutional convention.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Routt also succeeded in uniting the factions of the local Republican party.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] In the 1860s, the Colorado Territory, which had been created in 1861, was already relatively close to statehood.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] A Republican-dominated congress had passed an enabling act in 1864, that was signed by President Abraham Lincoln.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The first proposed state constitution was voted down by the voters of the territory on October 11, 1864.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] A second proposal for a state constitution was then ratified by the voters on August 12, 1865.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] President Andrew Johnson, who had come into office after Lincoln's assassination, opposed statehood for the Colorado Territory fearing a strengthened Republican majority.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] During his term, President Johnson successfully blocked all further attempts by Congress to force statehood for the territory.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] After Johnson left office in 1869, Congress failed to pass a statehood bill on three separate occasions in between 1869 and 1873.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The appointment saga around Governor McCook had shown the population of the territory the need for self-government and contributed to a strong effort towards statehood.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] An act of Congress was again necessary for statehood.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] After the 1874 United States elections, control of the 44th Congress was divided, with Republicans still firmly in control of the Senate but Democrats with a newly gained majority in the House.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] National Democrats had long been opposed to statehood for the Colorado Territory fearing that statehood would add a solid Republican state to the Union.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Patterson, who was a strong proponent of statehood, worked on convincing Democrats in Congress that Colorado would elect Democratic members to Congress.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Patterson pointed to his own election as proof.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] On the Republican side, former Delegate Jerome B.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Chaffee, also a statehood proponent, made sure that Republican member of Congress would remain convinced that Colorado would vote Republican and that they supported the party's line.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Republicans pushed statehood through the 43rd Congress in the last days of its term, as the Democrats would take over control of the House of Representatives after the 44th Congress was sworn in on March 4, 1875.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The United States Congress passed an enabling act on March 3, 1875, specifying the requirements for the Territory of Colorado to become a state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Grant signed a proclamation admitting the state of Colorado to the Union as the 38th state and earning it the moniker "Centennial State".
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The borders of the new state coincided with the borders that had been established for the Colorado Territory.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The enabling act laid out the process for the attempt at the first state constitution for Colorado.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The territorial governor was authorized to call an election for 39 delegates within 90 days of September 1, 1875 which had to convene for the convention within 60 days of such elections.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The crafted would have to be ratified by a referendum in July 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The enabling act had included a section stating that only those eligible to vote in territorial elections could vote in the referendum and in the prior elections for delegates to the constitutional convention.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] This meant that, due to territorial statue of 1868, only white males over the age of 21 were allowed to vote.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The act also included constraints for the future state constitution.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] It specified that the constitution could make no "civil or political distinction on the account of race or color" and that it had to "tolerate all religious sentiments".
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Governor John Routt ordered elections for representatives in a Constitutional Convention, which were held on October 25, 1875.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Republicans won 24 seats, while the Democrats won just 15 seats.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The convention convened in Denver on December 20, 1875.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The most hotly contested issues were the regulation of railroads, mines and other companies, women's suffrage, funding for denominational schools and whether God should be mentioned in the preamble.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The state constitution gave black men over the age of 21 the right to vote in state, while women's suffrage was also proposed but defeated in a 28–4 vote.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Delegates were afraid that territory's male electorate was against women's suffrage and that including it would doom the constitutions and thus statehood in the referendum.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The fear of corruption due to the strong influence of private mining and railroad companies in the state defined many choices of the convention.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The term length of Governors was set at just two years to give voters an early opportunity to reject unpopular administration.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Article V, Section 25, prohibited the passing of any laws benefiting just one company and Sections 27 and 28 provided ethics standards for legislators.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The constitution is also very long due to detailed instructions and restrictions of the legislative abilities of the Colorado General Assembly.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The intent here was to curb the ability of business leaders to enact laws through their influence over legislators.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The constitution passed the convention on March 14, 1876, in a unanimous vote of 30–0, with nine delegates absent.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Due to provisions in the enabling act, the ratification referendum could not be held until July 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The new constitution was finally ratified by a vote of the people on July 1, 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Only four counties, El Paso, Huerfano, Las Animas and Pueblo, voted against the constitution.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] At the time, the residents of those counties were mostly of Mexican heritage and the results showed their dissatisfaction with the constitution and their mistrust towards the majority Anglo-American population.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The Republican convention was held on August 23, 1876, in Pueblo.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Chaffee, who was considered the leader of the local Republican party, chaired the convention.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] When the convention convened in the morning of August 23, it was uncertain who the state party would choose as their first nominee for Governor.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Former Governor Samuel Hitt Elbert still enjoyed significant support among the delegates and the party leaders.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Elbert was considered the favorite for the nomination.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] His removal from office in 1874 had caused widespread solidarity and his candidacy was supported by Chaffee.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Incumbent Governor John Long Routt had still to fight against his image as an outsider and "carpetbagger".
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Although, Routt had gained respect among Republicans for successfully uniting the factions within the party.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Lafayette Head was a candidate who had strong support among the delegates from the Hispanic-majority southern part of the new state but a limited appeal outside his geographic base.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Chilcott was another candidate who was seen favorably by the party's establishment.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] After four rounds of balloting had ended without a candidate receiving a majority of the delegates' votes (see below), John Routt struck a deal with Lafayette Head and Samuel Elbert.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Head joined Routt on the Republican ticket as the nominee for Lieutenant Governor, while Elbert accepted a nomination in the elections for the Colorado Supreme Court.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes was already rumored to be the likely first Democratic nominee for governor.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes was born in Carlisle, Kentucky in 1817.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] He had worked as a transportation businessman, developer, and attorney in Missouri and Kansas.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] In Missouri, Hughes had also served in the Missouri House of Representatives and had been appointed Receiver of Public Moneys by President John Tyler.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] He practiced as an attorney in the city and was the first president of the Denver Pacific Railway and Telegraph Company.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] In 1875, he was elected to the Territorial Council, the upper house of the Colorado Territory legislature.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] On 29 August, the Democratic convention met in Manitou Springs to nominate candidates for the first state elections on 3 October.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes was nominated for governor by acclamation.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The slightly over one month long campaign began right after the conventions in the end of August 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Both nominees had very different styles of campaigning.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes hold many speeches presenting his platform.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] In the first three weeks of September 1876 alone, he travelled for campaign events to 15 different Colorado cities, speaking up to six nights per week.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The Republican newspaper Golden Weekly Globe, published an extensive report on Hughes's speech in Golden.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] In their report, the newspaper alleged that Democratic presidential nominee Samuel J.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Tilden had committed perjury and criticized Hughes for his defense and support of Tilden.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The editorial also criticized Hughes' language, as he used phrases like "damned lie" and "the government is going to hell", despite the fact that there were around twenty women in the audience.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] On the other hand, Democratic newspapers enthusiastically supported Hughes' candidacy.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] This was especially the case with the Denver Mirror, a small newspaper which was published by Stanley G.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The Republican nominee, Territorial Governor John Routt, did not make any public speeches during the campaign.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] He preferred to meet and greet voters face-to-face.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] At one Republican event, Routt acknowledged that he was not using rhetorical skills like his opponent.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] The first cartoon was published on September 17, 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Fowler was successful with his cartoons, which were received attention across the whole state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Routt was amused by the caricatures and began to distribute copies of them at his campaign events.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Routt was able to secure another term in office as Republicans managed to sweep all statewide offices and both chambers of the Colorado General Assembly.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Routt won the gubernatorial election by 14,154 to 13,316 votes, a 52–48 margin.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Source: 1877 Legislative Manual of the State of Colorado.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Many Colorado Democrats questioned the accuracy of the election results.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes did not approve the calls for a recount and refused to request one despite the closeness of the results.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] John Routt was sworn in as Colorado's 1st Governor on November 3, 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Routt did not run for reelection in 1878 but served another term as Colorado's as 7th Governor from 1891 to 1893.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Additionally, he also served as Denver's 17th Mayor from 1883 to 1885.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] John Routt died in Denver on August 13, 1907.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] After the lost gubernatorial election, Bela Hughes mostly retreated from politics.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] His advice was still sought but he never ran for public office again.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] In February 1877, he was suggested by the newspaper Memphis Appeal as United States Secretary of State, in case Democratic nominee Samuel J.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Tilden would emerge as the winner of the contested 1876 Presidential election.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes focused on his law practice in which he was in 1888 joined by his relative Charles J.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes Jr., who went on to represent Colorado as a Democratic member in the United States Senate.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Bela Hughes retired from his profession as a lawyer in 1893.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Hughes was recognized for his significant contributions to the state in the Colorado Hall of Fame and is depicted in the Colorado State Capitol.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-colorado-gubernatorial-election] Bela Hughes died in his Denver home in the early morning of October 3, 1902.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] The **1876–77 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between June 5, 1876, and March 13, 1877.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 45th United States Congress convened on October 15, 1877.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] The size of the House increased to 293 seats with the addition of the new state of Colorado.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] These elections coincided with the (heavily contested) election of President Rutherford B.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] Hayes' Republican Party was able to recover from the Democratic Party many of the seats it had lost two years before as the economy improved slightly.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] However, the Democrats retained a majority and were able to use the people's lack of interest in Republican Reconstruction-led projects to help keep crucial seats.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] Republican congressional leadership had a difficult time distancing itself from the corruption of the Ulysses S.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] Grant administration or the legislature's impact on the economy downturn.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] The previous election included 4 Independents, in Illinois and Massachusetts.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] In 1845, Congress passed a law providing for a uniform nationwide date for choosing Presidential electors.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] This law did not affect election dates for Congress, which remained within the jurisdiction of State governments, but over time, the states moved their congressional elections to this date as well.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] In 1876–77, there were still 8 states with earlier election dates, and 1 state with a later election date.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] Alabama redistricted and eliminated its at-large seats, going from 6 districts and 2 at-large seats to 8 districts.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] The state also elected a full delegation of Democrats, voting out the two Republicans.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] There were two elections to the new state of Colorado.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] Connecticut had been electing is members late in the cycle, even after the terms had begun.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] But starting in 1876, the state joined the others in electing its members on the November 7, 1876 Election Day.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p01] The delegation remained 3 Democrats and 1 Republican.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-colorado-p02] Wisconsin elected eight members of congress on Election Day, November 7, 1876.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **1876 United States presidential election in Colorado** took place on November 7, 1876, as part of the 1876 United States presidential election.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The state legislature chose three representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president, which would be the first and only time the state would do so.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado voted in its first ever presidential election, having become the 38th state on August 1 of that year.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The state cast three electoral votes for the Republican candidate Rutherford B.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] This proved to be decisive as Hayes would win the electoral vote by a margin of one vote.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Had Colorado not been a state in time for the 1876 election, Hayes would have lost the 1876 election to Democratic candidate Samuel J.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] The **1876–77 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with Rutherford B.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1876 and 1877, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] In these elections, terms were up for the senators in Class 2.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Although the Republican Party maintained their Senate majority, the Democratic Party gained five seats.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] After the November 15, 1876 elections in the new state of Colorado.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] In these elections, the winners were seated during 1876 or in 1877 before March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] In these regular elections, the winners were elected for the term beginning March 4, 1877; ordered by state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] In these elections, the winners were elected in 1877 after March 4.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] The special election in Pennsylvania was held March 20, 1877.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Republican Senator Simon Cameron had been elected to the United States Senate by the Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, in 1867 and was re-elected in 1873.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Following the resignation of Simon Cameron, the Pennsylvania General Assembly convened on March 20, 1877, to elect a new Senator to fill the vacancy.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Former United States Secretary of War J.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Donald Cameron, Simon Cameron's son, was elected to complete his father's term, set to expire on March 4, 1879.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Since his initial election in 1870, the Democratic Party had taken control of the Texas Legislature, ensuring that a Democrat would replace him.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Incumbent governor Richard Coke defeated former Texas Supreme Court justice John Ireland on the third ballot.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Representative John Hancock and former governor Fletcher Stockdale also ran, but they dropped out after the second round of balloting.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Caperton died July 26, 1876, in his second year in office.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Fellow-Democrat Samuel Price was appointed August 26, 1876 to continue the term, pending a special election in which he was a candidate.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Price lost the election to Democratic congressman Frank Hereford January 26, 1877 on the fourth ballot.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Appointed incumbent Samuel Price and challengers Frank Hereford and Henry S.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Walker, three prominent state Democrats, fought for the party's nomination over seven ballots and three sessions, without much movement in any direction.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] On January 26, with the Democrats unable to make a nomination, legislative Republicans broke the deadlock by throwing their support to Hereford on the floor.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Hereford resigned from the House January 31, 1877, thereby qualifying for the Senate.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] He only finished the term and left office in 1881.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Davis was re-elected January 26, 1877 on the third ballot.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1876-united-states-senate-elections-in-colorado] Davis would retire after this second term, in 1883.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The **1878–79 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between June 3, 1878, and September 3, 1879.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 46th United States Congress convened on March 18, 1879.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Elections were held for all 293 seats, representing 38 states.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This was the last election cycle that at least one state held its regular congressional election in an oddnumbered year.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] These elections occurred in the middle of President Rutherford B.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] With a sour economy as the nation's pressing issue, both major parties lost seats to the new Greenback Party, which was established to promote the long-term use of paper money as a solution to stop enormous economic fluctuations.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] The Democratic Party remained the largest party, but lost its majority.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] However, it allied with several independent politicians and was able to remain in power.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This was the fourth and last recorded House election where both major parties lost seats at the same time.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In most states, the elections were held November 5, 1878.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In 1845, Congress set a uniform nationwide date for choosing presidential electors.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] This Act of Congress did not affect election dates for Congress, which remained within the jurisdiction of state governments, but over time, the states moved their congressional elections to this date as well.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] California's elections were the last time a state held congressional general elections after November.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Elections are listed by date and district.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Patterson successfully contested the election and was seated March 4, 1877.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] In the 2nd district the difference between the two candidates, in the initial returns, was just 22 votes.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p01] Bisbee challenged Hull's election, and was eventually awarded the seat on January 22, 1881.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] South Carolina was rampant with voter fraud, particularly through the use of tissue ballots, thin ballots hidden in the normal ballot, typically 10 to 20 at a time.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] The almost statewide exclusion of Republicans as Commissioners of Elections, and the ensuing appointment of nearly all Democratic Managers of Elections, allowed to Democratic Managers to perpetrate this scheme.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] When the votes were counted and more votes than voters were found, the Managers removed and destroyed the Republican ballots resulting in the complete takeover of the state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/1878-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-colorado-p02] Wisconsin elected eight members of congress on Election Day, November 5, 1878.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The **2008 United States presidential election in Colorado** took place on November 4, 2008, as a part of the 2008 United States presidential election throughout all 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Voters chose nine representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for president and vice president.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado was won by Democratic nominee Barack Obama by a margin of victory of 8.95%.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The state was heavily targeted by both campaigns, although, prior to the election, all 17 news organizations actually considered this a state Obama would win, or otherwise considered as a safe blue state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Bush narrowly carried the state in 2004, Colorado ultimately flipped to Obama.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] This was the first time since 1992 in which the state was won by a Democrat in a presidential election, as well as the first of currently five consecutive times since 1944 in which it voted differently than Montana, another Rocky Mountain state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Key to Obama's victory was Democratic dominance in the Denver area, sweeping not just the city but also the heavily populated suburban counties around Denver, particularly Adams, Arapahoe, and Jefferson counties, as well as winning Larimer County, home to Fort Collins.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Obama also took over 70% of the vote in Boulder County, home to Boulder.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] McCain's most populated county wins were in El Paso County, where Colorado Springs is located, and Weld County, home to Greeley.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado served as the tipping-point state for Obama's overall victory in the presidential election - that is, the first state to give a candidate their 270th electoral vote when all states are arranged by their margins of victory.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] There were 16 news organizations who made state-by-state predictions of the election.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Pre-election polling taken in Colorado prior to the election mostly showed Obama with a slight lead.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The average of the last three polls showed Obama leading McCain 52% to 45%.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] John McCain raised a total of $3,491,086.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Obama and his interest groups spent $10,410,669.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] McCain and his interest groups spent $9,818,077.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] McCain/Palin visited the state 13 times.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Changing demographics and a growing Hispanic population made the state more favorable to the Democrats, although Republicans still had a hold on the state due to the party's conservative stances on social issues like abortion, gay rights, and gun control.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Like most of the Mountain West, Colorado had been traditionally Republican beginning with the Eisenhower landslide of 1952, in which Eisenhower overperformed throughout the region.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Between 1952 and 2004, inclusive, Democrats prevailed in Colorado only in 1964 and 1992—the former, a national Democratic landslide; the latter, a three-way contest in which independent candidate Ross Perot had disproportionate strength in the West.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] In addition, Republicans had mostly held control of the state legislature and most statewide offices since the 1960s.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Recently, however, there had been a growing population of Hispanic Americans, young professionals, and an influx of people from other states - all of whom tend to vote Democratic.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] These demographic changes caused the state's political ideology to shift.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] While Republicans still enjoyed an advantage in voter registration statewide, Democrats had been closing the gap.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] There had also been an increasing number of unaffiliated, independent-minded voters.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Since 2004, Democrats had won the governorship, both Senate seats, three House seats, and control of both chambers in the state legislature.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] At the presidential level, Colorado voted for Bush by 8.36% in 2000, making it the second-closest of the states carried by Dole in 1996 (behind only Virginia).
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Moreover, his 50.75% vote share was his lowest in any of the states carried by Dole in 1996, with Ralph Nader posting a relatively strong showing in the state in 2000.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Bush's relatively narrow margin in the state in 2004, along with the demographic changes of the prior four years, led Colorado to become a crucial swing state in 2008.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Both Barack Obama and John McCain campaigned extensively in the state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Several factors in the campaign favored the Democrat.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Barack Obama did very well in the caucus, defeating opponent Hillary Clinton with almost 67% of the vote.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] On the other hand, John McCain badly lost the state to opponent Mitt Romney, who gained 60% of the vote.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Moreover, the 2008 Democratic National Convention was held in Denver.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The publicity generated from the event provided a strong boost to Obama.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] According to Real Clear Politics polling averages, Obama and McCain were neck-to-neck through the summer and early September.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] However, as the 2008 financial crisis hit, Obama's numbers in Colorado jumped to over 50%.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] During the campaign, several media organizations reported on voting machine problems.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] There was also reporting on the controversial practice of "purging" voter registration lists.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] On election day, Obama won by a comfortable margin, greater than his national average.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Obama improved on John Kerry's performance throughout the state.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] He won landslides in the Democratic strongholds of Denver and Boulder; in both areas, Obama took more than 70% of the vote.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] He also further built upon Kerry's strength in a number of rich counties dominated by ski resorts along the Front Range; and continued to dominate the traditionally Democratic areas of Pueblo County, Adams County, and the thinly populated, Latino counties of southern Colorado.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] McCain did best in the rural, conservative areas next to Kansas and Utah, where he won by landslide margins.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] In Rio Blanco County, Mesa County, Yuma County, Washington County, Lincoln County, Bent County, Crowley County, and tiny Dolores County, Phillips County, Cheyenne County, and Kiowa County, he managed a slightly greater vote share than Bush in 2000.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Voters in more populated El Paso County, home to conservative Colorado Springs, gave McCain a 19% margin, which, while a comfortable win, was far less than Bush's 35% margin in 2004.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] McCain also won two other relatively populated counties, Douglas County and Weld County, both outer suburbs of the Denver area—although, again, by substantially reduced margins compared to Bush in 2004.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] However, the largest suburban counties of the area, traditionally Republican Jefferson, Larimer, and Arapahoe Counties voted Democratic for the first time since 1964.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Broomfield County, which cast its first presidential vote for Bush in 2004, also flipped to Obama.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Altogether, this was more than enough to overcome Republican advantages elsewhere in the state, as Obama won it by a nearly nine-point margin.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Elsewhere in the state, Democrats also did well.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Democrat Mark Udall defeated Republican Bob Schaffer for an open U.S.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Senate seat; his vacated House seat was also won by Democrat Jared Polis.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] In addition, Democrat Betsy Markey defeated incumbent Republican Marilyn Musgrave, by 12 points for Colorado's 4th Congressional District seat.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] At the state level, Democrats picked up one seat in the Colorado Senate, but lost two seats in the Colorado House of Representatives.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Obama's 65.8% victory in Summit County was the highest percentage win by a Democratic presidential nominee in the county since Woodrow Wilson won the county with 70.3% of the vote back in 1916.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] While Barack Obama won the state's popular vote and nine electoral votes, John McCain carried four of the state's seven congressional districts, including two seats held by Democrats.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Technically the voters of Colorado cast their ballots for electors: representatives to the Electoral College.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Colorado is allocated 9 electors because it has 7 congressional districts and 2 senators.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] All candidates who appear on the ballot or qualify to receive write-in votes must submit a list of 9 electors, who pledge to vote for their candidate and their running mate.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Whoever wins the majority of votes in the state is awarded all 9 electoral votes.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Their chosen electors then vote for president and vice president.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Although electors are pledged to their candidate and running mate, they are not obligated to vote for them.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] An elector who votes for someone other than their candidate is known as a faithless elector.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The electors of each state and the District of Columbia met on December 15, 2008, to cast their votes for president and vice president.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The Electoral College itself never meets as one body.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] Instead the electors from each state and the District of Columbia met in their respective capitols.
[src:2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado/2008-united-states-presidential-election-in-colorado] The following were the members of the Electoral College from the state.
